Import Libraries

In[19]:
import librosa
import librosa.display
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

from IPython.display import Audio

Load the Audio File

In[7]:
# Path to your audio file
#source: https://freesound.org/people/manuke/sounds/315880/
audio_path = '../audio/315880__manuke__tokyo-mall-1.wav' 

# Load the audio file
y, sr = librosa.load(audio_path, sr=None)  # Use original sample rate
duration = len(y) / sr

print(f"Sampling Rate: {sr} Hz")
print(f"Audio Duration: {duration:.2f} seconds")

Sampling Rate: 44100 Hz
Audio Duration: 127.08 seconds

Visualize the Waveform

In[8]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
librosa.display.waveshow(y, sr=sr)
plt.title("Waveform of Tokyo Mall Ambiance")
plt.xlabel("Time (s)")
plt.ylabel("Amplitude")
plt.show()

Generate and visualize the spectrogram

In[10]:
D = librosa.amplitude_to_db(np.abs(librosa.stft(y)), ref=np.max)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
librosa.display.specshow(D, sr=sr, x_axis='time', y_axis='log')
plt.colorbar(format='%+2.0f dB')
plt.title("Spectrogram of Tokyo Mall Ambiance")
plt.show()

Extract Audio Features

Zero-Crossing Rate (Measures Signal Changes)

In[11]:
zcr = librosa.feature.zero_crossing_rate(y)
print(f"Mean Zero-Crossing Rate: {np.mean(zcr):.4f}")

Mean Zero-Crossing Rate: 0.0488

Spectral Centroid (Frequency "Center of Mass")

In[14]:
spectral_centroid = librosa.feature.spectral_centroid(y=y, sr=sr)
print(f"Mean Spectral Centroid: {np.mean(spectral_centroid):.2f} Hz")

Mean Spectral Centroid: 2196.29 Hz

Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients (MFCCs)

In[16]:
mfccs = librosa.feature.mfcc(y=y, sr=sr, n_mfcc=13)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
librosa.display.specshow(mfccs, x_axis='time', sr=sr)
plt.colorbar()
plt.title("MFCCs of Tokyo Mall Ambiance")
plt.show()

Compute the dominant freq

In[18]:
# Compute the FFT
fft = np.abs(np.fft.fft(y))
frequencies = np.fft.fftfreq(len(fft), 1/sr)

# Focus only on positive frequencies
positive_freqs = frequencies[:len(frequencies)//2]
positive_fft = fft[:len(fft)//2]

# Find the dominant frequency
dominant_freq = positive_freqs[np.argmax(positive_fft)]

print(f"Dominant Frequency: {dominant_freq:.2f} Hz")

Dominant Frequency: 388.67 Hz

Generate the tone

In[20]:
# Parameters for the sine wave
duration = 5.0  # Duration in seconds
sampling_rate = 44100  # Sampling rate (standard for audio)

# Time axis
t = np.linspace(0, duration, int(sampling_rate * duration), endpoint=False)

# Generate the sine wave at 388.67 Hz
frequency = 388.67  # Dominant frequency in Hz
y = 0.5 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * frequency * t)  # Amplitude scaled to 0.5

# Plot the waveform
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
plt.plot(t[:1000], y[:1000])  # Plot a small portion to visualize the wave
plt.title("Generated Sine Wave at 388.67 Hz")
plt.xlabel("Time (s)")
plt.ylabel("Amplitude")
plt.show()
In[21]:
# Play the generated tone
Audio(y, rate=sampling_rate)
